<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Although closely related to 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. fasciger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="fasciger">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. fasciger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. terebratus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="terebratus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. terebratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which have among the longest emboli and copulatory ducts in sitticines, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Attulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Attulus pubescens" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pubescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Attulus pubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has among the shortest known in sitticines. The very large RTA is distinctive. Introduced to North America in the 20th century (
<bibRefCitation author="Cutler, BE" journalOrPublisher="Peckhamia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="91 - 92" refId="B6" refString="Cutler, BE, 1990. Synanthropic Salticidae of the Northeast United States. Peckhamia 2: 91 - 92" title="Synanthropic Salticidae of the Northeast United States." volume="2" year="1990">Cutler 1990</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
